    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-01T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-01T12:00:00-05:00" n="405"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d405">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/5–154: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-01T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 1, 1954—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 67. Repeated information London 105.
                    British tell us that at <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName>’s
                    luncheon yesterday for <persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_CEL1">Chou En-lai</persName>, host raised no question of
                    substance but seemed interested rather in encouraging cordiality between his
                    guests. <persName corresp="#p_CEL1">Chou</persName> said he would like to see
                    better relations with <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>. <persName
                        corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName> replied relations were two–way street, that
                    Britain had recognized Communist China but that latter seemed reluctant to
                    recognize Britain. <persName corresp="#p_CEL1">Chou</persName> dwelt on theme
                    that China under Peking Government was world factor which could not be ignored
                    and was being unrightfully deprived of its position as member of <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>. <persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName> said
                    that this was question quite apart from subject under consideration at Geneva
                    and he did not wish to discuss it.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
